The paper deals with a voting process on graphs, which involves interactions between neighbouring vertices. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category. The paper also discusses the expected time to reach consensus, which is a measure of the efficiency of the voting process. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. The paper also considers the underlying graph structure and the update rules for the voting process, which suggests that the paper could belong to the Graph Theory (cs.GT) and Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. Finally, the paper uses mathematical analysis to derive results for the expected time to reach consensus, which suggests that the paper could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category.
